						<h2>About</h2>
						<p>Nature already removes about half of our annual CO2 emission through biotic and abiotic means. </p>
						<p>Rock and mineral weathering is an abiotic process that already removes XXXX tons of CO2. As rocks and minerals decay, elevated CO2 reacts with the surface water to create carbonic acid. Through a series of naturally occurring chemical reactions, CO2 reacts with rocks to create a material called bicarbonate. Bicarbonates are the largest carbon reservoir on Earth's surface, holding the equivalent of 139,000 gigatons of CO2. Rock and mineral weathering is a significant but slow example of nature's CO2 removal process. As rocks and mineral decay, elevated CO2 acidifies surface water making carbonic acid. This carbonic acid reacts on contact with the very large alkaline mineral reservoir of sand on the Earth’s crust consuming the acidity, removing CO2 and forming dissolved mineral bicarbonates. These bicarbonates then enter the ocean. Ocean bicarbonate is the largest carbon reservoir on the Earth’s surface (38,000 gigatonnes carbon primarily as dissolved bicarbonate or the equivalent of 139,000 Gt CO2).</p>
						<p>Electrogeochemistry refers to the electrochemical acceleration of this geochemistry. Electrogeochemistry builds off rocks and minerals' natural weathering by strategically placing common alkaline rocks and minerals within a saline water electrolysis cell. When powered by renewable energy, electrogeochemistry produces a solution that spontaneously converts to dissolved mineral bicarbonate and creates hydrogen gas (H2). When added to the ocean, these mineral bicarbonates would further increase alkalinity in seawater and help counter ocean acidification. Variations on this technology could also have the additional environmental benefits of cleaning wastewater, cooling the surface ocean and/or providing carbon and nutrients for marine aquaculture. The H2 produced can be substituted for fossil transportation fuel or it can be converted back to electricity using a fuel cell.  </p>
						<p>Electrogeochemistry technology has the ability to not only remove CO2 from the environment but also reduce CO2 emissions by generating hydrogen fuel that can be used as a substitute for fossil fuels.</p>
